title = "Welding Processes Overview and Selection"

content = """
Welding is a fabrication process that joins metals by melting base material, typically with a filler metal, to form a strong metallurgical bond upon cooling. At Ridgecrest Metalworks, welding operations are central to assembly of structural frames, pressure vessels, machine bases, and complex fabrications. Selecting the appropriate welding process is the first step in producing a sound, cost-effective weld.

The major arc welding processes used at Ridgecrest include GMAW (MIG), GTAW (TIG), SMAW (Stick), and FCAW (flux-cored). Each has different characteristics in terms of productivity, weld quality, positional capability, operator skill requirement, and applicable materials.

GMAW (Gas Metal Arc Welding, commonly called MIG) is the workhorse process for steel and aluminum fabrication. A continuously fed wire electrode is shielded by an externally supplied gas mixture. It is fast, semi-automatic, and adaptable to all positions with proper parameters. Suitable for carbon steel, stainless steel, and aluminum.

GTAW (Gas Tungsten Arc Welding, TIG) uses a non-consumable tungsten electrode and requires filler rod to be fed manually. It produces the highest-quality welds with excellent control, very clean appearance, and suitability for thin material and exotic alloys. It is slower than GMAW and demands high operator skill.

SMAW (Stick) uses a consumable coated electrode that provides both filler metal and shielding. It is portable, tolerates contaminated base metal better than other processes, and requires no external shielding gas. It is used for heavy structural work, repair, and outdoor environments.

FCAW uses a tubular wire electrode with flux inside. It combines the productivity of GMAW with better penetration and tolerance to surface contamination. Gas-shielded FCAW (FCAW-G) requires external shielding gas; self-shielded FCAW (FCAW-S) generates its own shielding from the flux, allowing outdoor use without gas.

Process selection criteria include: joint thickness and geometry, required weld quality and NDT requirements, base metal and filler metal compatibility, welding position, production volume, and environment (shop vs. field). Welding procedures (WPSs) at Ridgecrest specify the required process and parameters for each application and must be followed.
"""

